    <h2 id="meetings">Meeting Phrases</h2>
    <p><strong>会议 (huìyì)</strong> meeting. <strong>让我们开始吧 (ràng wǒmen kāishǐ ba)</strong> Let's begin. <strong>关于这个问题 (guānyú zhège wèntí)</strong> Regarding this issue. <strong>我同意 (wǒ tóngyì)</strong> I agree. <strong>我们需要讨论 (wǒmen xūyào tǎolùn)</strong> We need to discuss this.</p>

    <h2 id="email">Email Etiquette</h2>
    <p>Chinese business emails follow formal patterns. Begin with <strong>尊敬的X先生/女士 (zūnjìng de... xiānsheng/nǚshì)</strong> — Dear Mr./Ms. End with <strong>此致敬礼 (cǐ zhì jìnglǐ)</strong> — Respectfully. Use 您 (nín, formal you) rather than 你 throughout.</p>

    <h2 id="networking">Networking and Small Talk</h2>
    <p>Business card exchange remains important: present with both hands and read the card before putting it away. Common networking phrases include <strong>互相学习 (hùxiāng xuéxí)</strong> — let's learn from each other — a humble way to suggest collaboration. <strong>保持联系 (bǎochí liánxì)</strong> means "stay in touch."</p>

